  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering BacklogView Styling**\n\nI\'m currently focused on styling the `BacklogView.tsx` component with the Natural Tones theme. The initial step involves adapting the general container; for instance, changing the root wrapper\'s background and text colors. Subsequently, I\'ll be adjusting the header area\'s background and text properties to align with the theme. The plan is to create a seamless integration with the natural tone palette.\n\n\n**Refining Component Styles**\n\nI\'m now diving into the granular styling for the `BacklogView`, specifically the header and \"+ Create Sprint\" button. I\'m focusing on text and background colors, font weights, and sizes. I\'m aiming for a cohesive look using a Natural Tones theme. The goal is to ensure a clean, intuitive, and visually appealing header, with the \"+ Create Sprint\" button taking a prominent but elegant position. I\'m working on the design for the Sprint Creator Form, making sure it visually integrates with the rest of the styling.\n\n\n**Styling Buttons and Sections**\n\nI\'ve been working on the granular styling, specifically button styles for the form. I\'m focusing on the \"Cancel\" and \"Submit\" buttons, getting the text colors, sizes, and backgrounds right using classes from the `natural` theme. The goal is to make these visually distinct and intuitive. I\'m also styling the Sprint containers in the `BacklogView` - particularly the section headings and main block. I\'m using appropriate text sizes, fonts and border styles to match the overall theme.\n\n\n**Detailing UI Element Styles**\n\nI\'m now deep-diving into the styling of individual UI elements within the `BacklogView`. I\'m meticulously defining styles for item counts, active sprint badges, and progress stat icons. I\'m focusing on text sizes, colors, and border styles. The goal is a consistent and informative visual language. For header actions, I\'m working on complete and start sprint button styling, covering states like hover and disabled. I am currently integrating the visual language from the existing theme to apply to these new components. Also, I\'m also styling the appearance when the subtasks/issues list is empty.\n\n\n**Defining List Component Styles**\n\nI\'m now focusing on specific styles for the list items in the BacklogView. I\'m styling individual list components and list row containers with padding, background color, and border settings, including hover states. I\'m also styling the Issue Key, summary text, and status badges, aiming for clarity and visual consistency. I\'m customizing the `getStatusBadgeClass` with specific styling for each status type, and adding styling for the story point badges.\n\n\n**Styling New Creator Components**\n\nI\'m now styling the Quick Issue Creator components within the BacklogView list, focusing on the destination sprint selector with specific padding, border, and hover state. The creator row itself gets a distinct background, border, and padding. I am working on the styles for select issue type inputs, input boxes, \"Add\" buttons with distinct colors, and the \"Cancel\" buttons. The goal is to provide a smooth, intuitive, and cohesive experience.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 34
      nanos: 422617590
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
