    thinking: "**Applying Natural Tones**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the `IssueDetailDrawer.tsx` file. My goal is to completely implement the Natural Tones styling throughout this critical user view. I\'m starting with the outer drawer container, specifically lines 222-225, where I\'ll be replacing the current styling.\n\n\n**Implementing Drawer Changes**\n\nI\'ve updated the outer drawer container, replacing the original Tailwind classes with new ones for fixed positioning, natural background, and animations. Next, I replaced the drawer header\'s styling, updating padding, border, and background to incorporate the new natural tones. I\'ve also adjusted text colors for project header info and delete/close buttons. Finally, I\'ve styled the primary left content section with a natural background and styled the summary input, too.\n\n\n**Refining AI Action Box**\n\nI\'ve just finished styling the AI Agile Copilot Actions Box within the `IssueDetailDrawer.tsx`.  I replaced the original Tailwind classes with a new natural tone scheme, focusing on subtle backgrounds and borders.  I\'ve paid close attention to the button styles, ensuring a consistent aesthetic with variations for hover states and button types. Lastly, I refreshed the AI points result display to reflect these design improvements.\n\n\n**Styling Issue Description**\n\nI\'m now integrating natural tones for description labels, textareas, and the rendered markdown display. I\'ve updated the styling of the description label, edit markdown links, and save links. Textareas now have rounded corners and subtle border, while the rendered markdown utilizes the \'prose\' style with custom classes, maintaining readability and aesthetic consistency. I\'m also addressing the subtasks section\'s styling.\n\n\n**Updating Subtask Styles**\n\nI\'m now styling the subtask section to match the natural tone theme. Specifically, I\'m working through the styling for individual subtask rows. I\'ve updated the row\'s design to include a white background, hover effect, rounded corners, and a subtle border. I\'ve restyled the checkbox, delete links, and input fields to fit the natural tone design. I\'ve also integrated the \"Add\" button with corresponding natural classes. Finally, I\'ve started the comment thread section.\n\n\n\n**Styling Comment Thread**\n\nI\'ve just added the styling for the comment thread section, focusing on its visual appeal and readability. The save comment button uses natural primary colors. Comment items now feature a white background, rounded corners, and a subtle border. I\'ve restyled comment headers, delete links, and bodies with appropriate natural tone classes, enhancing the visual hierarchy and aesthetics. Now, I\'m working through the attributes sidebar column.\n\n**Styling Attributes Sidebar**\n\nThe attributes sidebar column is now styled. The container uses a natural sidebar background and subtle border with rounded corners. I\342\200\231ve styled the labels with a neutral tone and uppercase text. Lastly, the dropdown selects now have a white background, rounded corners, and focus effects to maintain consistency.\n\n\n**Applying Work Log Styling**\n\nI\'m now integrating natural tones for the Work Log sub-sections within the IssueDetailDrawer.tsx file. I\'ve focused on styling the various elements of the Work Log, applying classes to refine the visual style. The hours label now has uppercase text. I also updated the clock trigger, the logging form\'s container, and the hours and description input fields. I\'ve styled the \"Log Work\" button with natural tones, and applied natural classes to the work logs list elements and date stamps to reflect the design updates.\n\n\n"
